# GetX State Management Patterns

## Controller Architecture

### Base Controller
All controllers should extend [BaseViewController](mdc:lib/core/controller/base_view_controller.dart) for lifecycle management:

```dart
class FeatureController extends BaseViewController {
  // Controller implementation
}
```

### Controller Structure
Follow this pattern for all controllers:

```dart
class FeatureController extends BaseViewController {
  // 1. Dependencies
  final FeatureRepository _repository = FeatureRepository();
  
  // 2. Form management
  GlobalKey<FormState> formKey = GlobalKey<FormState>();
  TextEditingController textController = TextEditingController();
  
  // 3. Observable state variables
  RxBool isLoading = false.obs;
  RxBool isError = false.obs;
  RxString errorMessage = ''.obs;
  RxList<DataModel> dataList = <DataModel>[].obs;
  
  // 4. Lifecycle methods
  @override
  void onInit() {
    super.onInit();
    _initializeData();
  }
  
  @override
  void onReady() {
    super.onReady();
    // Called after widget is rendered
  }
  
  @override
  void onClose() {
    // Dispose controllers and resources
    textController.dispose();
    super.onClose();
  }
  
  // 5. Public methods
  Future<void> performAction() async {
    // Implementation
  }
  
  // 6. Private methods
  void _initializeData() {
    // Private initialization
  }
}
```

## State Management Patterns

### 1. Reactive Variables
Use `Rx` types for reactive state:

```dart
// Boolean states
RxBool isLoading = false.obs;
RxBool isVisible = true.obs;

// String states
RxString selectedValue = ''.obs;
RxString errorMessage = ''.obs;

// List states
RxList<String> items = <String>[].obs;
RxList<UserModel> users = <UserModel>[].obs;

// Object states
Rx<UserModel?> selectedUser = Rx<UserModel?>(null);
```

### 2. State Updates
Update reactive variables using `.value` or assignment:

```dart
// Update boolean
isLoading.value = true;
// or
isLoading(true);

// Update string
errorMessage.value = 'Error occurred';
// or
errorMessage('Error occurred');

// Update list
items.add('New item');
items.removeAt(0);
items.clear();

// Update object
selectedUser.value = newUser;
```

### 3. State Observers
Use `ever`, `once`, or `debounce` for reactive programming:

```dart
@override
void onInit() {
  super.onInit();
  
  // React to changes
  ever(isLoading, (bool loading) {
    if (loading) {
      // Show loading indicator
    } else {
      // Hide loading indicator
    }
  });
  
  // React once
  once(selectedUser, (UserModel? user) {
    if (user != null) {
      // Navigate to user profile
    }
  });
  
  // Debounce search
  debounce(searchQuery, (String query) {
    _performSearch(query);
  }, time: Duration(milliseconds: 500));
}
```

## UI Integration Patterns

### 1. GetBuilder for Specific Controllers
Use `GetBuilder` when you need to rebuild specific parts of the UI:

```dart
class FeatureView extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return GetBuilder<FeatureController>(
      builder: (controller) => Scaffold(
        body: Column(
          children: [
            Text('Count: ${controller.count}'),
            ElevatedButton(
              onPressed: controller.increment,
              child: Text('Increment'),
            ),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

### 2. Obx for Reactive Updates
Use `Obx` for automatic reactive updates:

```dart
class FeatureView extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      body: Obx(() => Column(
        children: [
          Text('Count: ${controller.count.value}'),
          if (controller.isLoading.value)
            CircularProgressIndicator(),
        ],
      )),
    );
  }
}
```

### 3. GetX for Full Controller Access
Use `GetX` for full controller access with reactive updates:

```dart
class FeatureView extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return GetX<FeatureController>(
      builder: (controller) => Scaffold(
        body: Column(
          children: [
            Text('Count: ${controller.count}'),
            if (controller.isLoading)
              CircularProgressIndicator(),
          ],
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

## Dependency Injection with Bindings

### 1. Binding Structure
Create bindings for each feature:

```dart
class FeatureBindings extends Bindings {
  @override
  void dependencies() {
    // Lazy initialization - created when first accessed
    Get.lazyPut<FeatureController>(() => FeatureController());
    Get.lazyPut<FeatureRepository>(() => FeatureRepository());
    
    // Permanent - created immediately and never removed
    Get.put<ApiService>(ApiService(), permanent: true);
    
    // Async initialization
    Get.putAsync<DatabaseService>(() async {
      final db = DatabaseService();
      await db.initialize();
      return db;
    });
  }
}
```

### 2. Binding Registration
Register bindings in [routes.dart](mdc:lib/routes/routes.dart):

```dart
List<GetPage> pages = [
  getPage(
    name: RoutesName.featureView,
    page: () => const FeatureView(),
    binding: FeatureBindings(),
  ),
];
```

### 3. Dependency Access
Access dependencies in controllers:

```dart
class FeatureController extends BaseViewController {
  // Direct access
  final FeatureRepository _repository = Get.find<FeatureRepository>();
  
  // Or with null safety
  FeatureRepository get repository => Get.find<FeatureRepository>();
}
```

## Form Management

### 1. Form Controllers
Use `TextEditingController` for form inputs:

```dart
class SignInController extends BaseViewController {
  GlobalKey<FormState> formKey = GlobalKey<FormState>();
  
  TextEditingController emailController = TextEditingController();
  TextEditingController passwordController = TextEditingController();
  
  @override
  void onClose() {
    emailController.dispose();
    passwordController.dispose();
    super.onClose();
  }
}
```

### 2. Form Validation
Use the [ValidationMixin](mdc:lib/core/utils/validation_mixin.dart) for form validation:

```dart
class SignInController extends BaseViewController with ValidationMixin {
  String? emailValidator(String? value) => emailValidator(value);
  String? passwordValidator(String? value) => passwordValidator(value);
  
  Future<void> onSignIn() async {
    if (formKey.currentState?.validate() ?? false) {
      // Proceed with sign in
    }
  }
}
```

## Error Handling

### 1. Error State Management
Handle errors with reactive variables:

```dart
class FeatureController extends BaseViewController {
  RxBool hasError = false.obs;
  RxString errorMessage = ''.obs;
  
  Future<void> loadData() async {
    try {
      isLoading(true);
      hasError(false);
      
      final result = await _repository.fetchData();
      result.when(
        (data) {
          dataList.value = data;
        },
        (error) {
          hasError(true);
          errorMessage.value = error;
        },
      );
    } catch (e) {
      hasError(true);
      errorMessage.value = 'An unexpected error occurred';
    } finally {
      isLoading(false);
    }
  }
}
```

### 2. Error Display
Show errors in UI:

```dart
Obx(() {
  if (controller.hasError.value) {
    return Text(
      controller.errorMessage.value,
      style: TextStyle(color: Colors.red),
    );
  }
  return SizedBox.shrink();
})
```

## Best Practices

### 1. Controller Lifecycle
- Always call `super.onInit()`, `super.onReady()`, and `super.onClose()`
- Dispose text controllers in `onClose()`
- Use `onInit()` for initialization
- Use `onReady()` for post-render operations

### 2. State Updates
- Use `.value` for single updates
- Use direct assignment for multiple updates
- Avoid unnecessary reactive variables
- Use `Obx` for simple reactive updates

### 3. Performance
- Use `GetBuilder` for specific controller updates
- Use `Obx` for reactive variable updates
- Avoid deep nesting of reactive widgets
- Dispose controllers properly

### 4. Testing
- Mock dependencies in tests
- Test controller logic separately
- Use `Get.testMode = true` for testing
- Test error scenarios

### 5. Memory Management
- Always dispose text controllers
- Use `lazyPut` for non-essential dependencies
- Remove controllers when not needed
- Monitor memory usage in development